---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { meta } from '../../data/snapshot';

// Scenario grid — intensive margin. Excess cost = base × exposed fraction × premium.
const scenarios = [
  { name: 'Low', base: '$20B', frac: '75%', exposed: '$15B', prem: '80bp', cost: '~$0.12B' },
  { name: 'Central', base: '$83B', frac: '~48%', exposed: '~$40B', prem: '90bp', cost: '~$0.36B' },
  { name: 'High', base: '$200B', frac: '30%', exposed: '$60B', prem: '110bp', cost: '~$0.66B' },
];
---
<Base
  title="The Cost of an Unfinancialized Compute Market · CCIR Research"
  description="A working estimate of what the compute market pays in excess cost of funds for having no way to hedge and trade compute forwards — the price of not being financialized. Hypothetical."
  ogImage="/og/home.png"
  showTape={false}
>
  <section class="wrap top">
    <header class="page-head">
      <div class="kicker">Research · Market Structure · {meta.as_of_date}</div>
      <h1>The Cost of an Unfinancialized Compute Market</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        A working estimate of what the compute market pays, in excess cost of
        funds, for having no way to hedge and trade compute forwards — the price
        of not being financialized.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="body">
      <h2>The question</h2>
      <p>
        If a liquid, low-basis, cleared compute-forward curve existed, GPU and
        AI-compute borrowers could sell forward the cash-flow-certainty
        component of their revenue and finance on contracted rather than
        uncontracted terms. This estimates the annual excess cost of funds the
        sector bears today for the <em>absence</em> of that market.
      </p>

      <h2>The lever, precisely</h2>
      <p>
        The peer-reviewed power-project-finance literature separates two things
        an offtake contract bundles: <strong>counterparty credit</strong> (will
        the customer pay) and <strong>cash-flow certainty</strong> (is the
        revenue locked). A price hedge buys only the second. Gohdes, Simshauser
        &amp; Wilson (<em>Energy Economics</em>, 2022) isolate it: a fully-contracted
        plant finances ~<strong>90bp</strong> tighter, at much higher gearing,
        than an uncontracted one on cash-flow certainty <em>alone</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        So the premium here is the <strong>~90bp certainty slice</strong> — not
        the ~225bp CoreWeave DDTL 4-vs-5 gap or the ~700bp IG-vs-non-IG gap,
        which bundle counterparty credit a hedge cannot repair. Those are
        carried only as upper bounds.
      </p>

      <h2>The model</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Intensive margin</strong> (the headline): excess annual interest
        = exposed debt stock × certainty premium, where the exposed stock is the
        portion of GPU/AI-compute debt financed <em>without</em> cash-flow
        certainty — uncontracted, or contracted-but-not-bankable.
      </p>

      <div class="grid-wrap">
        <table class="data grid">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Debt base</th><th>× Exposed</th><th>= Exposed $</th><th>× Premium</th><th>Excess / yr</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {scenarios.map((s) => (
              <tr class={s.name === 'Central' ? 'central' : ''}>
                <td class="nm">{s.name}</td><td>{s.base}</td><td>{s.frac}</td><td>{s.exposed}</td><td>{s.prem}</td><td class="num">{s.cost}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="headline">
        <strong>~$0.15–1.0 billion per year today, central case ≈ $0.4 billion.</strong>
        Roughly half of the ~$83B GPU-collateralized book is financed as though
        its cash flows were uncontracted; the ~90bp certainty slice would strip
        that spread out — about $0.4B a year at today's stock.
      </p>

      <h2>What drives the range — and why it's the point</h2>
      <p>
        The answer is governed almost entirely by the <strong>exposed-base
        fraction</strong>, not the premium. On a revenue basis the sector looks
        ~98% contracted, arguing for a small exposed sliver — but
        <em>contracted ≠ bankable</em>: counterparty concentration
        (one hyperscaler at 62–72% of a borrower's revenue), sub-IG offtakers,
        tenor mismatch (2–5yr contracts vs ≥5yr debt vs 2–3yr GPU life), and a
        growing short-tenor inference tail. The true exposed share is
        <strong>genuinely unobservable</strong> — which is itself the argument
        for a neutral reference. The premium (~90bp) is peer-reviewed and moves
        the answer ~1.4×; the exposed base moves it ~7×.
      </p>

      <h2>Why "today" understates it</h2>
      <p>
        The cost scales with the debt stock, and the stock is early. Against
        Morgan Stanley's ~$1.5T data-center financing gap over 2025–28, the
        exposed-eligible book builds toward $500B–$1T. At 50% exposed × 90bp
        that is <strong>~$2–5 billion per year by 2028</strong> — on debt the
        sector is already committed to building.
      </p>

      <h2>The larger, conditional prize</h2>
      <p>
        The bigger channel is financing that never happens. Uncontracted
        structures size debt at ~50% advance and ~2× coverage — roughly half the
        debt per dollar of cash flow. A hedge could roughly double debt capacity
        against the same cash flows, substituting cheap debt for expensive
        equity. But this is realized <strong>only if the benchmark is liquid,
        low-basis, and cleared</strong> — the freight-derivatives history is
        explicit that a reference without a clearing venue does not move
        financing terms. We keep it out of the headline.
      </p>

      <h2>Caveats</h2>
      <ul class="caveats">
        <li>Premium is the certainty slice only (~90bp); the 225/700bp spreads bundle counterparty credit and are upper bounds.</li>
        <li>The exposed fraction is a modeled scenario, not a measurement — the single largest source of range width, stated deliberately.</li>
        <li>Hedges are imperfect substitutes (basis, shape, volume risk persist); the certainty slice is narrowed, not closed.</li>
        <li>Value grows as the forward curve lengthens toward the ~5yr debt tenor; the extensive margin is conditional on a cleared venue.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="method">
        Method: certainty-premium from Gohdes/Simshauser/Wilson (2022,
        <em>Energy Economics</em> v114); debt base from the
        <a href="/credit">CCIR credit ledger</a> (GPU-collateralized subset) and
        BIS / Morgan Stanley sizing; exposure framework from lender and
        rating-agency criteria. A CCIR working estimate — figures are ranges.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <style>
    .top { padding-top: 32px; }
    .page-head { max-width: 80ch; margin-bottom: 8px; }
    .page-head h1 {
      font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-3xl);
      line-height: var(--lh-display); font-weight: var(--weight-display);
      margin: 6px 0 12px;
    }
    .standfirst em { font-style: italic; color: var(--accent); }

    .body { max-width: 80ch; }
    .body h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-xl);
      margin: 28px 0 8px;
    }
    .body p {
      font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-md);
      color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 14px;
    }
    .body p em { color: var(--accent); font-style: italic; }
    .body a { color: var(--accent); }
    .headline {
      border-left: 2px solid var(--accent); padding: 4px 0 4px 16px;
      margin: 18px 0 !important; font-size: var(--fs-lg) !important;
    }
    .headline strong { color: var(--ink); }

    .grid-wrap { border: 1px solid var(--rule); background: var(--surface); overflow-x: auto; margin: 8px 0 18px; }
    table.grid { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-family: var(--font-mono); }
    table.grid th { text-align: right; font-size: var(--fs-xs); color: var(--ink-dim); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: var(--tracking-eye); }
    table.grid th:first-child, table.grid td.nm { text-align: left; }
    table.grid td { text-align: right; font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--ink); }
    table.grid tr.central { background: var(--surface-2); }
    table.grid tr.central td.nm { color: var(--accent); font-weight: var(--weight-strong); }
    table.grid td.num { color: var(--accent); font-weight: var(--weight-strong); }

    .caveats { max-width: 84ch; margin: 4px 0 18px; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
    .caveats li { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--ink-dim); line-height: 1.55; }
    .method {
      font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs) !important;
      color: var(--ink-faint) !important; line-height: 1.7 !important;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); padding-top: 14px; margin-top: 24px !important; max-width: 90ch;
    }
    .method a { color: var(--accent); }
  </style>
</Base>
